    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA67-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pakaṟkuṟi vantu nīṅkun talaimakaṉait tōḻi varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante asked HIM for mariage who was leaving after having come to the day tryst</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA67">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            cēyvicum pivarnta ceḻuṅkatir maṇṭila</l>
<l>            mālvarai maṟaiyat tuṟaipulam piṉṟē</l>
<l>            yiṟavarunti yeḻunta karuṅkāl veṇkuruku</l>
<l>            veṇkōṭ ṭaruñciṟait tāa yakkaraik</l>
<l>            karuṅkōṭṭup puṉṉai yiṟaikoṇ ṭaṉavē </l>
<l>            kaṇaikkāṉ māmalar karappa malkukaḻit</l>
<l>            tuṇaiccuṟā vaḻaṅkalum vaḻaṅku māyiṭai</l>
<l>            yellumiḻ paṉikkaṭaṉ malkucuṭark koḷīi</l>
<l>            yemarum vēṭṭam pukkaṉa rataṉāṟ</l>
<l>            ṟaṅki ṉevaṉō teyya poṅkupicir </l>
<l>            muḻavicaip puṇari yeḻutaru</l>
<l>            muṭaikaṭaṟ paṭappaiyem muṟaivi ṉūrkkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent2">When the full-beamed disk that climbed the distant sky</l>
<l rend="indent">had hidden behind the big mountains,</l>
<l rend="indent3">the ghat became lonely.</l>
<l>The black-legged white egrets that had risen to eat prawn,</l>
<l rend="indent">spread [their] white-tipped rare(?) wings [and] took [their] seat</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the Puṉṉai tree with black branches on that shore.</l>
<l>And our people have entered the hunt,</l>
<l rend="indent">kindling light-emitting<note place="foot">Here the word order is slightly awkward. We would prefer <term xml:lang="ta">el-umiḻ</term> actually to precede the <term xml:lang="ta">cuṭar</term>, but then the composition might be due to metrical reasons.</note> lamps to increase [their sight of] the chilly sea</l>
<l rend="indent2">to that place, where sharks in company are wandering [their] route<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vaḻaṅkalum vaḻaṅkum</term> can safely be understood as a figura etymologica, but what of the <term xml:lang="ta">-um</term>? One way of explaining it would be to read two sentences, coordinating the <term xml:lang="ta">vaḻaṅkalum</term> with <term xml:lang="ta">emarum</term>, but then it would have to be quite an asyndetic coordination.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">in the backwaters that rise to hide the round-stalked big blossoms.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Therefore,</l>
<l>what if [you] stayed in the village<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ūrkku</term>: how to explain the dative here? We expect a locative, if any mark at all.</note> of our residence</l>
<l rend="indent2">with gardens by the breaking sea, where waves rise up</l>
<l rend="indent2">with drum-sound [and with] foaming spray?</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
